Introduction During the past two decades, the size of system addressable with computer simulations has gradually increased, allowing the inclusion of biochemistry as an area of research that can beneÔ¨Åt from this powerful investigation tool. Considering speciÔ¨Åcally force-Ô¨Åeld-based all-atom approaches, this has been possible thanks to the following achievements: enhanced computer power has now reached memory and speed requirements sufÔ¨Åcient to treat explicitly solvated proteins; new and more efÔ¨Åcient techniques to sample conÔ¨Ågurational space have been proposed [1,2]; and force-Ô¨Åeld parameterization ‚Äî optimized through a continuous and ongoing validation process ‚Äî has become accurate enough to explain and predict experimental results [3,4].
Ten or hundred nanosecond simulations of proteins in an explicit aqueous environment are currently feasible. However, most of the relevant dynamics and interactions

within cells (typically, protein‚Äìprotein docking, rearrangement upon ligand binding or after biochemical reactions, folding) occur on the timescale of microseconds or milliseconds, and involve large macromolecular aggregates. In these processes, the number of degrees of freedom is at least one order of magnitude and the timescale four to six orders of magnitude larger than what is currently feasible with all-atom simulations. Furthermore, in some cases, atomically detailed simulations might not be the most appropriate, as an increasing number of biomolecular aggregates are being studied experimentally using low to medium resolution techniques (such as cryo-EM and small-angle X-ray scattering [5,6]). Thus, the idea of using simpliÔ¨Åed descriptions through the ‚Äòintegration‚Äô of a large number of degrees of freedom into a few ‚Äî ‚Äòcoarse graining‚Äô ‚Äî arises spontaneously. Coarse-grained approaches, which have been around for years [7], have recently enjoyed renewed interest. With respect to earlier studies, a larger variety of different simpliÔ¨Åed descriptions and more rigorous methodologies for the parameterization are currently being proposed.
This review provides a classiÔ¨Åcation of currently used coarse-grained models for macro-biomolecular systems, focusing on the most recent applications and pointing out the innovative aspects. The bead models, that is, models based on a united-atom representation of the amino acid (involving one to six interacting centers), are presented. In general, as the number of beads decreases, the simulation is less expensive and the system that can be simulated is larger. However, parameterizing force-Ô¨Åelds that are both accurate and transferable ‚Äî that is, capable of describing the general dynamics of systems with different compositions and different conÔ¨Ågurations ‚Äî becomes increasingly difÔ¨Åcult as the graining becomes ‚Äòcoarser‚Äô, because more speciÔ¨Åc interactions must effectively be included in fewer parameters and functional forms. For this reason, most currently popular coarse-grained models are parameterized based on a single reference conÔ¨Åguration and the dynamics they reproduce are strongly biased towards it [8,9]. Different models represent different compromises between accuracy and transferability, with different degrees of independence from the reference conÔ¨Åguration. Recent methodologies for ‚Äòextreme‚Äô coarse graining are also reported, based on different mathematical approaches for the integration of the degrees of freedom.
Elastic network models In elastic network models (ENMs), the system is represented by a network of beads connected by elastic springs (see Figure 1), usually one bead per amino acid (although

