Proteins 2004, 57:725-733. A method is presented that uses ENM to automatically decompose a protein into structural domains, deÔ¨Åned as portions of the protein that move independently. The accuracy of the method is veriÔ¨Åed for a large set of proteins and connections with graph theory are indicated.
12. Wu Y, Yuan X, Gao X, Fang H, Zi J: Universal behavior of localization of residue Ô¨Çuctuations in globular proteins. Phys Rev E 2003, 67:041909.
13. Burioni F, Cassi D, Cecconi F, Vulpiani A: Topological thermal  instability and length of proteins. Proteins 2004, 55:529-535. ENM is used to analyze the relationship between topological thermal instability and the size of proteins. A general relationship is demonstrated

between the size of the protein and the ‚Äòdegree‚Äô of topological connectivity.
14. Zhang Z, Shi Y, Liu H: Molecular dynamics simulations of  peptides and proteins with ampliÔ¨Åed collective motions.
Biophys J 2003, 84:3583-3593. ENM is used to compute the principal modes along a full-atom MD trajectory and amplify them to better explore the phase space. The method is applied to T4 lysozyme and to the refolding of an S-peptide analog.
15. Kim MK, Li W, Shapiro BA, Chirikjian GS: A comparison between  elastic network interpolation and MD simulation of 16S
ribosomal RNA. J Biomol Struct Dyn 2003, 21:395-405. An efÔ¨Åcient method based on ENM for generating conformations that interpolate between two different conformations is demonstrated and applied to 16S rRNA. The resulting conformations are compared with an all-atom MD simulation.
16. Micheletti C, Carloni P, Maritan A: Accurate description of  protein vibrational dynamics: comparing molecular dynamics
and Gaussian models. Proteins 2004, 55:635-645. An ENM based on Ca and Cb positions is proposed; it has the same computational complexity of a one-bead ENM and is proven to give a better accuracy.
17. Delarue M, Dumas P: On the use of low-frequency normal modes to enforce collective movements in reÔ¨Åning macromolecular structural models. Proc Natl Acad Sci USA 2004, 101:6957-6962.
18. Hinsen K, Reuter N, Navaza J, Stokes DL, Lacapere J-J: Normal  mode based Ô¨Åtting of atomic structure into electron density
maps: application to SR Ca-ATPase. Biophys J 2005, 88:818-827. An ENM with distance-dependent elastic constants was used together with NMA to Ô¨Åt sarcoplasmic reticulum Ca-ATPase into electron density maps. Atomically detailed structures are obtained and conclusions are drawn about phosphorylation-induced conformational changes of the protein.
19. Chacon P, Tama F, Wriggers W: Mega-dalton biomolecular  motion captured from electron microscopy reconstructions.
J Mol Biol 2003, 326:485-492. ENM and NMA are used to reconstruct the fundamental motions of bacterial RNA polymerase, the 30S and 50S subunits of the ribosome, and the chaperonin CCT.
20. Tama F, Miyashita O, Brooks CL III: Normal mode based Ô¨Çexible  Ô¨Åtting of high-resolution structure into low-resolution
experimental data from cryo-EM. J Struct Biol 2004, 147:315-326. A method for Ô¨Åtting high-resolution structures into low-resolution experimental data is shown. The method is based on ENM and NMA, and allows protein Ô¨Çexibility by taking into account conformational changes induced by interactions between structures. The method is applied to elongation factor G bound to the ribosome, Escherichia coli RNA polymerase and cowpea chlorotic mottle virus.
21. Kundy S, Jernigan RL: Molecular mechanism of domain swapping in proteins: an analysis of slower motions. Biophys J 2004, 86:3846-3854.
22. Tama F, Valle M, Frank J, Brooks CL III: Dynamic reorganization  of the functionally active ribosome explored by normal mode
analysis and cryo-electron microscopy. Proc Natl Acad Sci USA 2003, 100:9319-9323. The slower motions of the 70S ribosome from T. thermophilus are analyzed with ENM and NMA. Mechanical rearrangements that appear to be related to function are highlighted and are shown to agree with cryoEM data.
23. Isin B, Doruker P, Bahar I: Functional motions of inÔ¨Çuenza virus hemagglutinin: a structure-based analytical approach. Biophys J 2002, 82:569-581.
24. Keskin O, Bahar I, Flatow D, Covell DG, Jernigan RL: Molecular mechanisms of chaperonin GroEL-GroES function. Biochemistry 2002, 41:491-501.
25. Navizet I, Lavery R, Jernigan RL: Myosin Ô¨Çexibility: structural  domains and collective vibrations. Proteins 2004, 54:384-393. An ENM of scallop myosin is reported and a method for the analysis of the rigid blocks of the protein is presented. Regions that have a key role in the change of rigidity of the protein are detected and analyzed.

