Scheraga and co-workers over the past few years. The beads are located on the Ca atom, on the centroid of the sidechain and on a ‚Äòpeptide‚Äô (p) center located midway between two Ca atoms. However, Ca is only used to calculate the position of p; thus, the degrees of freedom correspond to a two-bead model. The parameterization is based on the statistical analysis of structures and on Ô¨Åtting the free energy functions obtained from full-atom simulations of oligopeptides. Additional terms account for correlation between the degrees of freedom. The model has been recently optimized to include ellipsoid sidechains and interaction parameters with calcium, and used in protein structure and interaction prediction.
56. Zacharias M: Protein docking with a reduced protein model  accounting for side-chain Ô¨Çexibility. Protein Sci 2003,
12:1271-1282. A model with one bead for the Ca atom and up to two beads for the sidechains was used in a protein‚Äìprotein docking approach. Size and hydrophilic/hydrophobic interactions are accounted for by van der Waals like amino-acid-speciÔ¨Åc terms. Sidechain conformational changes are taken into account by introducing several different rotamers of the sidechain during docking. This procedure is shown to generate more accurate complex structures than rigid docking.
